A Republican strategy to hamper Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy on the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth and claims that electoral fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people who die from the fall of a lightning bolt.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of election fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Contrary to what happens in Canada, U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And in that same line a majority of American governments enacted, starting in 2009, new laws that made the registration or voting process difficult.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, during 2011, 180 bills were introduced that restricted the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, as well as proof of U.S. citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the screening, and revoke the right to vote to citizens with criminal background.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to submit a photo ID.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
As a result, the Republican authorities hastened to extend that practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to submit a photo ID.
It is important to note that, contrary to what is happening in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as the Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, i.e. 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
But, often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
As a result, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 and 20 per cent of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states students, the voters who vote most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, those same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for Republican parties to use the documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to make such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws that require voters to prove they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Spanish vote.
It seems that two out of every three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers backed certain laws in 2011 that abolished voter registration on the same day of scrutiny in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a support service for voters who wanted to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of around 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 have reduced the enrollment rate of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers passed laws in five other states that favored reducing the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 Florida election, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state’s voters.
In the case of Hispanics, the same thing happened.
These represent only 11% of voters, which is equivalent to 24% of citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76 percent of the electorate, represent no more than 46 percent of citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have fiercely opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
In this regard, the Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney’s Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
It was possible, in part, to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states passed the law requiring the submission of a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, since it is clear that with them it is intended to influence the 2012 results in the key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have passed such laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say for sure whether these legislative changes at the electoral system scale will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
