The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson generated a great shock last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of all that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what is more, it is the particle whose existence predicted the standard model: our best or "less bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists it is not entirely clear that it is Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data revealed this week at a major physics congress held in Kyoto seems to confirm that it is, although more data is missing to be completely safe.
Anyway, we assume it's Higgs, since the chances of getting it wrong seem few. We'll see what it's about.
There is, in this great world, a generalized and unavoidable law which implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There’s no way to break that rule and don’t try too hard, because it will end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, roughly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we meet the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli’s beginning.
And on the other hand there are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories which, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, of which we shall not speak here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be of some form.
These bosons, I might point out here, are not the exotic bugs that we might believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or "light particle" that acts as the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “disorders” the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone at a pond.
In this “disorder” an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing more than a photon; that is, one of the “force carrier” bosons.
More Stable Field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it, you need to reach extremely high energies, a bit like a frozen pond where only a thick rock could slide across the surface.
That’s why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN’s (the great Hadron Collider is a ring of 27 km in circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself stuck to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not.
Now, what “can they contribute” to all these investigations?, asks Mrs. Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between observations and predictions of MS.
On the other hand, many want them to find each other, as the slightest difference could open a door to a “new physics” that taps certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (ups!).
But we have not found such differences at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of such research in our day-to-day are difficult to predict, but we do not believe we are wrong to say that we will not have any.
To see: in the early 1960s, laser pioneers in laboratories did not at all suspect the revolution that their work would provoke.
They interviewed the scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who made the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962, was at first considered a "laboratory device".
Just imagine...
And in addition, applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light sensor in 1969 in the course of his research into optics.
Although it wasn’t his original intention at all, this pickup now serves as the “eye” for all the digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
That doesn’t mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but you never know...
