A Constitution with forceps in Egypt
It is a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which gives it provisionally full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
He caught everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Only a week ago, the Head of State had given two more months to the Assembly to complete its work.
And for almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial clutter.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president persevered in his “autocratic delirium” and continues to “treasure his word” and “smear the right.”
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that this is a measure to end the institutional and political crisis faster and speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their plan to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy wreaks havoc across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in his favor, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this resource has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "either they vote my text or I keep the full powers", powers that are supposed to come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamist, voted the text yesterday.
The majority of the Liberals did not attend the call.
By mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not validate their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, yesterday morning 11 people, alternate members, were added in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As you might expect, the articles voted unanimously.
The commentators are pleased, on the other hand, that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been practically expressed at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent's watch was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which is the subject of all eyes, remains at last identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that “the principles of Sharia constitute the main source of law”.
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental claim, hoped that "principles" could be replaced by "standards", which would have allowed for stricter application.
For Islamists, that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it to be nothing more than an advertising scam.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm their compliance with Sharia laws.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "the people called to pronounce are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy.”
The fears of liberals are further heightened by the fact that the next rector of such a university would be much less moderate than the current one.
“For now, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are in the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas, but university students, some of them trained in the French system,” explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity about article 220, as the terms used mimic the religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent are the civil judges competent to pronounce themselves above all this.”
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms regarding the extended powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few compared to those they were during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
According to the wishes of the military, the revision of the defense budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defense council.
Prosecutions of civilians in military courts will also not be banned, as requested by human rights associations.
They also showed their concerns regarding the text, which they consider libertarian.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive has been the prohibition of torture in accordance with article 36.
The word was not in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was due to leave last night on television, protests are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state protested on Saturday.
