You talk about the problems of our country with the transfer of the legislation regulating the practice of public procurement.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it an office similar to our NK<0xC3><0x9A> or is it organized in a different way?
In so far as the offices, such as the NK<0xC3><0x9A>, there is the Bundesrechnungshof, with an organization similar to ours, with a school as well, the only thing is that in their case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
Competencies are also to a certain extent analogous, however, as Germany has a federal organization, the Courts of Auditors are even at this level. In this respect it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Accounts (BRH) can only control federal money, which here we call state funds.
Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
I would generally not like to make a comparison without specific data, but Germany remains a model in some respects, but it cannot be precise in what is better.
Could it be better, for example, with regard to the quality of inspectors?
Of course not, but, I repeat, I don’t like to make such comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries that we take as a model have to deal with a large number of problems.
If it wasn't, it wouldn't be of any benefit to you to collaborate with our office, wouldn't you think?
With regard to the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean to your Office, and does its impact in any way manifest?
Given that the validity period of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control actions.
Since we perform ex-post checks, we need to have a certain delay.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparation of future controls: we have launched a new tool of "detection of non-economic risks", by which we have passed almost 14,000 public tenders, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of selection process are corrected.
Do you believe that the passing of this law is beneficial or that it is rather a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulation "hardens" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already with the previous legislation, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programmes of the regional council), and any non-compliance with public procurement law meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to harden the law this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal ruling, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We’ll see where this path begins.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDG would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called <0xC5><0xA0>varc system, with reference to the fact of being autonomous only on paper.
Is the <0xC5><0xA0>varc system prohibited or allowed?
