Poland and the Cosmos.
At the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of the ESA, the second member of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland started an intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the following years participated in the Agency's project committee.
However, Poland’s path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in spaceflights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld's lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born in 1905) left the attendees indifferent and, years later, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a major driver of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, he was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when he put his name to one of the craters of the moon's hidden face.
As early as 1925, a trainer was built in Poland that was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is not known who was the author of the proposal and the details of the project are not known either.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for launching or braking.
The information about this dress is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
Beginning in 1933, Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to missiles.
The research was funded by the Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes clear that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric fighter missile designed by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakete - torpedoes airborne and aerial bomb", by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was in charge of all projects of missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the onset of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, for the first time reference is made to society with four very extensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, Prof. M. Subotowicze, proposed the creation of a society that would be devoted to cosmonautics.
Artificial satellite projects had already been launched at that time and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
From the beginning of 1956 the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of that year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Beginning in 1956, the PTA significantly participated in the development of the RM (Meteorologiczna) rocket, which was a success and became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first RM-1 was completed in 1957 and was first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had a peak of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and aerial testing of the RM-2 two-stage rockets began in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>d<0xC3><0xB3>w desert in the summer of 1959.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket in development was to be the object of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
In 1962, however, the work was suspended.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed from each other by the space available for scientific devices.
On the Meteor-1A rocket the available space for the volume was 0.4 liters, on the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters and on the Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum peak in the three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first aerial tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
As part of the Intercosmos program, Poland joined the cosmic space research on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
Suspension of the Social Work Act is not the solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court suspended the Social Works Act.
The resolution sparked a heated discussion in society.
It will certainly be interesting to look at the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulatory.
Consequently, this means that different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, along with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labour costs (of wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the importation of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and to this end "provokes a downturn" of the competitor's price with the aim of getting the most part of the market and thus increasing its profit margin.
Large-scale means, for most employers, moving production abroad, buying there cheaper or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in those countries where the price of labor, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and, therefore, is not responsible for the unemployment generated by this phenomenon, the social expenditure of the state necessarily increases.
All this causes the total disinterest of employers in paying taxes and offset the economic and social damages they have caused in their desire to make profits.
The situation is so universally known that it is not necessary to present specific statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the governments of these countries are forced to compete with the aim of artificially reducing the social level of their own population and thus attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments make private capital available to their own population without taking social decline into account.
This is especially evident in the changes in the laws in force.
The aim is to force the population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment, and, on the other hand, through the restricted right of employees with regard to labour rights.
The result is an increasing poverty along with the increasing differences between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot keep up with their own work.
The number of people who receive this kind of help is already reaching a million.
In the context of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, a fairly frequent case occurs: people employed with a salary so low that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
A scandal of this kind related to the situation of the assistant employees of the German federal parliament was made public.
The austerity measures of almost all the southern states of the EU undoubtedly lead to the same situation. People, pressured by an abysmal decline of their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the nineteenth century or to live with a very bad wage at the limit of society, in the hope that some day the country will be deprived of capital.
Is it necessary to ask where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty passes from one country to another or never arrives, since Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a small part of a European salary.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media assert to the satiation that the state should not contribute capital to the economy, that leading the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by meddling in control.
Then it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence with its selfishness in the political march and, therefore, in the whole state.
In this case, the answer is clearly yes.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and ubiquitous, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the field of corruption, in mutual favor, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is as follows: state ministries, in the absence of financial means, commission the drafting of bills to private legal firms, which are often linked to industry.
This type of bill is then passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
It is obvious that liberal-oriented democracies quickly find themselves in a situation like that described by Appian in his work The Crisis of the Roman Republic in the days of Caesar and Pompey: "The state had been disintegrating for some time and administrations were forcibly engaged."
In exchange for bribes, favors obtained illegally and help to finance stones or swords.
The bribery and corruption were spread without any impediment and the people went to the polls with the ballot in advance"... "there were no people with a character who aspired to a position in the administration, so once, it was necessary, because of this disorganization, the state was in a single place, in a single place, in a single place, in which there were no consuls"... "It began to be a serious one, in the state, in which was not a single place."
The conclusion, as in antiquity, is that today’s society is based on unconscionable preferences of individual benefit without taking into account common interests.
Private capital is not, in its essence, able to understand and claim the benefits of society as a whole.
The result is the same as then, an unprecedented decadence of the elite, without any effort being made to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal democracy, as a definite pause, pending the next coup.
