The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government’s negotiating intervention.
In the U.S., his fate caused a wave of solidarity and animadversion against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck themes an episode of this story, which was a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated journey, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian embassy.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, for this helped a covert story one extravagant point: they went out with Canadian passports, as members of the film crew examining the location in the country for the shooting of a science fiction superproduction.
Combination of genders
The plan drawn up by "exfiltration" expert Toni Mendez required Hollywood's collaboration.
To make the lie seem true, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production company even had a real office.
Details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a singular combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a hoax (an example may be the Ocean's Eleven series).
In the film the moods are combined. On the one hand we find well-documented sequences of Tehran. In the sequence of credits are shown emblematic photographs of the time of the events, which were shaped in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes are slightly lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And in addition, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: costumed men analyzing the situation at the negotiating table, in the office hallways, by phone...
Ben Affleck has been able to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been the subject of mockery, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Goodbye Little, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it’s Affleck’s first film in which the action doesn’t take place in the city of Boston, where it was raised.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed old film directors above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck demonstrates it in Argo, where Tehran is "wheeling" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of the real events. The introductory sequence of the taking of the embassy is impressive for its synoptic ability that, at the same time, conveys the emotion of the confusion and the lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, the story gives a step to the story.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect on the fictional scenes (the impostor team in Tehran’s bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story does not offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
Sometimes it adds something to the reality: here everything does not come out so elegant (the scene in which the crisis at Tehran airport, the diverting of a call to America and the unbridled quest for its track turn into a madness).
Argo’s weakness is the uncontrollability that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are not, much less, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck’s film loses a bit of dramatic trait, but it’s a film that can be followed with moderate interest, valuing its performance and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 1970s.
But if it collapses, that will be difficult.
As an evocation of a real story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of secret services can be, it is enough.
