The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that’s how political leaders decided that there was only one possibility to improve the statistics: you had to build a library!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a master in the art of bar charts and responsible for fun and cynical buildings, took the topic with her usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the competition in 2003 with five books under her arm and a smile on her face.
And as the jury looked puzzled around and shrugged, Maas proceeded to pile up the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here you have it, my proposal for the Spijkenisse book mountain, the so-called 'Bookenberg'."
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain rises in the planned location.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential and residential buildings.
At the beginning of November the Mountain of Books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small town lacking history, which to date had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and an incredibly ugly town hall behind which one would rather intuit a milky power station, now boasts a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to the book
The first impression is that it is a book paradise under a cheesecake.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountainous massif, but the true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with its topography at every step of its climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to embrace with the view, the glazed brick floor and the elegant lighthouses unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
As you look up, you can see the park benches, the dogs and the boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally the book shelves are arranged along the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade and in the center opens a huge dark room that is usually a bit uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
What we’ve done is put up the classic spatial configuration and take out the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain is very well exploited: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention is given to the black shelves that assume the functions of wall cladding, parapet and railing at the same time.
The sight, the touch and the smell are strange.
Even architects and civil engineers shake their heads more often when they hear about this unknown material.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, head of the project in the city of Spijkenisse.
And that is how one day, on a Frisian farm, we come across the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in the greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands, a plastic fabric of a few millimetres thick is used as a base to hold the roots of the crops.
This is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine tissue lasts two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, until plates of four centimeters thick were obtained.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a new mix of car and sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but you can also enjoy some tasty Dutch croquettes and its ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere at the same time that they maintain the atmospheric humidity suitable for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a New Soul
“Although it’s hard to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling is obtained from geothermal energy.
Despite the fact that the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden circles located transverse to the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade serve to give shade and absorb most of the sun’s rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is a matter of automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the sceptical worker in the information technology sector, has already dared to stand up in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has also been there.
Also, Chinese traditional medicine teacher Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library, calling the "Bookenberg" as Spijkenisse's "late soul".
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way, it is intended to fill, at the moment, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; it currently has 70,000 copies.
