Szabo: "The Germans must play a more protagonist role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-Europe relations, this puts Berlin in a rather pessimistic diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany indicated that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories observer status of the United Nations.
In the end, however, Berlin abstained.
What's the point?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, because of the special relationship that unites the country with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time, I don’t think it supports the American stance either.
Germany wanted to prove its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
It has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because at the moment he is reorienting his foreign policy, moving away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
Therefore, the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to doing so.
I think they’re still pondering what their role will be, but they’ve already started the road to a “normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries such as France or Britain.
What exactly does a "normal" foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy finds a strong motivation in economic policy, that is, in exports and in their relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken with regard to the conflict in the Middle East and the vote of the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason, it must be careful and not be alienated from Arab public opinion or from Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not give it such importance since it is not a totally unilateral relationship.
However, they do play a fundamental role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the United States by abstaining from voting on important decisions such as the Palestinian vote?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German attitude enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not believe that such a drastic rupture has occurred as in the case of Libya.
It may be that Germany has managed to cultivate some respect.
After all, all this has done is prove that it is a country that is taken seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
On the other hand, the U.S. has clearly shown itself in favor of a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
These disparities have always been due to U.S. domestic policy.
I believe that the Obama administration secretly shows great understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, it is obvious that the government cannot publicly defend that position.
I believe that the true disparity of views does not actually have the scope that is attributed to it.
If we look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is by no means enthusiastic about the policy he develops.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of its main partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that’s exactly what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but that is not the case.
Therefore, they do not have the possibility of being part of a higher entity, but they must push things from their own position.
That is exactly what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in forcing Europe to adopt a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, either simply because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a hot topic.
But I think the Germans are clear that they should play the role of an independent figure.
Does Germany see itself as an important international actor? Does Germany really want to take on a leading role?
Or is it still difficult for you to accept that leadership?
Germany has not yet gotten used to it, it is always something uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country is still struggling to play a more important role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that every time Germany positions itself as the main player, certain anti-German feelings are unleashed.
This is not easy for the Germans.
This is an old problem and is that no one wants to be surrounded by enemy countries.
In this way, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It should show a receptive attitude towards different neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
The U.S. influence on European policy is diminishing more and more, but the EU is not currently covering that gap, then who is left?
The Germans will have no choice but to take on a more protagonist role.
Even if they don’t like it, if they find it unpleasant or if it makes them an even more unpopular town, it’s life!
Stephen Szabo is Executive Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institution where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly discuss the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Mark Protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a world-renowned brand and Polo Ralph Lauren as well.
What is Armani Polo?
Behind this name is a name officially registered in China but that has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection while the real eponyms do not file a claim.
And even then it is not clear that they will be given the reason.
“Foreigns find it increasingly difficult to protect their brands in China,” says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at firm Taylor Wessing who specializes in violations of protection rights in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters to be able to register their marks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead Prada registers Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way, as happened to the Puma sportswear manufacturer.
Pattloch opens an archivist in which he holds seats at the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the Zegna DF Puma brand, an artificial name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In the big cities there are large warehouses of several plants dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch’s cases are of a different kind: on behalf of his clients, he is fighting the fact that the trade mark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or companion brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
It refers to women who have "fished" a rich man.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
“It’s detrimental to the business, we have to fight it,” Pattloch says.
“The brand makes water, the monopoly position disappears and the damage the image is suffering is enormous.”
The financial losses and procedural costs of the sectors concerned are millionaires, especially in the case of emblematic luxury products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, with a volume of 15 billion euros per year China is, in size, the third largest market for luxury goods and the fastest growing.
However, achieving the cancellation of registrations of dubious legality in the registration of trademarks is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
Processes can last up to nine years and the result is uncertain.
Pattloch speaks of cases in which the court rejected a lawsuit because it had been so long that the name that was the subject of the lawsuit had already become a “market reality”.
"If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarist because the process has damaged his mark in China," Pattloch said.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best-known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That’s why to this day the Chinese can continue to use a very similar emblem to the Mercedes star.
Volvo’s buyer, Geely, initially used a white and blue logo that was largely reminiscent of BMW; the matter was settled in court and Geely had to modify it.
The clothing manufacturer Lacoste lost in China against imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo represented a crocodile looking in the opposite direction to the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO brand office in Beijing recognizes that in 2010 they had difficulties due to the lack of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, “the labor emergency situation returned to normal.”
In this way, the number of unprocessed claim processes has been reduced by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 complaints are still pending resolution.
Fighting this costs a lot of money.
As is usual in China, the figures are surprising.
Last year, the CTMO registered more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
It would be a new record and means that China leads the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth consecutive year, according to the brand office.
It seems that this also happens with the number of valid logos, a figure that amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan would have been invested in rights.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese impersonator.
While the Germans have managed to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
the imitator has managed to secure the Chinese rights over the Freudenberg brand.
“We ourselves have provoked this situation because in Germany the surnames are not protected,” says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO trademark office also rejected the monks’ appeal.
In the following two instances they have given Freudenberg the right, but the opposite side continues to fight today.
You have to be very careful
Now the case has reached the doors of the High Court of Justice, where it is still pending a resolution.
Wentzler trusts in being able to resolve the issue favorably and praises the professionalism of the courts.
However, it also states that “the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time.”
It is difficult to estimate internal costs; the enterprise archive has had to review files up to a hundred years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg offered the opposing party a “six-digit sum in euros” with the aim of reaching a friendly agreement, but it was unsuccessful.
“This shows how much we care,” Wentzler says.
The dangers lurking in the Far East threaten even to affect Europe.
in particular if imitators are secured there the rights to unprotected trademarks.
A Chinese manufacturer tried to register in Germany the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather products.
The group has long since left this commercial area, but managed to prevent registration.
“We have to be very careful,” says Wentzler.
Both he and lawyer Pattloch recommend German companies to be extremely cautious when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trademark law, but what needs to be done is “register in China also everything that may be susceptible to protection,” as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the subject can be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, in case Freudenberg lost the last assault of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the opposing party licensing rights for his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or in the segment in question would drive us out of the market.
