There are people for whom their work is hell and another who literally works in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to descend every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulfurous gas that emanates from Earth’s bowels solidifies when it comes into contact with air.
After tearing off large sulfur rocks, which in total weigh about 70 kilograms, he carries them in two bamboo baskets that loads on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
They are only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters altitude, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to ascend to the step of a turtle, keeping the balance and carefully measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall down the precipice.
They know that any transpiration could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who was sacked years ago by the risks of the Kawah Ijen.
