It is about PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better, its workers, who pay 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) for every kilogram of sulfur.
He then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make cherries, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
“It’s normal to weigh 70 kilograms, so we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip,” explains Anto, who usually performs three daily ports.
It takes three hours in each and ends milled, but they allow you to add 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a misery for such inhuman effort, it is triple what it would gain in the field.
“The miners’ newspaper is very high here, where coffee collection is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” explains the carrier, who previously worked as a carpenter on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the cut was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason of weight that, in Indonesia, is as strong as the sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where I have stopped the Hindus."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto has been playing hide-and-seek in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to pay him a bill despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
It’s the price you have to pay to get your dream.
“I will work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French,” he promises in a more than acceptable English.
Punished for life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead does the work of a mule.
Sharing an unclean wooden cabin with other carriers, he gets up every day at two o’clock in the morning because the sulfur does not stop eating at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
