Despite its penguin benefits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur extraction to save costs or supplies any equipment to carriers, who work on their own and at both weight.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) camera surcharge that, alongside the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This job is for the beasts and not for the people,” Madrusin, a 42-year-old supply carrier who has been in the Kawah Ijen for three decades, has protested since leaving school.
Able to lift up to 110 pounds, he says he will endure working "everything he can" because he needs the money to educate his three children, aged 18 to 10.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although sulfur burns the throat and clears the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of suffering serious diseases... beyond, of course, of their usual respiratory problems, arthrosis, pain in the lips.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can only weigh 50 kilos at 53.
