“I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life,” Unainik proclaims, opening his mouth well, where he lacks several teeth.
Of his five children, the oldest, 30, also works loading sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates generation after generation one of the hardest trades in the world: the one done by the human mules of the Kawah Ijen.
