Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became world famous for his central role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R.", in the television series "Dallas", in which he played an unscrupulous, malicious and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as predator oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas," died Friday afternoon from complications from cancer, according to a statement from the family provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., the production house of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, once again representing the iconic role he liked most," the family said.
Larry’s family and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for Thanksgiving.
Linda Gray, who played her wife's role in the original series and in the sequel, was with Hagman when she died in a Dallas hospital, her publicist, Jeffrey Lane, said.
It brought joy to everyone I knew.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him a lot.
"He was an original person and lived life to the fullest," Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and admitted he had been drinking a lot for years.
In 1995, he was found a malignant tumor in his liver and underwent a transplant.
Years before "Dallas", Hagman became famous on television as a decent guy in the light comedy "I Dream of Jeannie", broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
She played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life is altered when she meets an attractive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and takes her to live with him to his home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Her film work included critically acclaimed roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the charmingly disgusting J.R. that led Hagman to his highest stardom.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in its orbit aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional phrase "Who shot J.R.?", thought to generate expectations around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman's character is nearly murdered, generated international speculation and millions of dollars risked in betting houses.
It also helped give the series a record audience at that time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 chapter, an average of 41 million viewers tuned it and turned "Dallas" into the second-most-viewed entertainment program in history, behind the end of "MASH" in 1983, which had 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. got her pregnant and then threatened to spot her as a prostitute unless she was out of town, but others also had reasons to attack him.
Hagman portrayed Ewing as an insatiable corrupt man with a charismatic smile: a cheating businessman and an unfaithful husband who tried to get his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), to be interned.
“I know what I want in J.R.’s tombstone,” Hagman said in 1988.
I should say, "Here lies the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only deal he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, reminded Hagman on Friday of someone "huge, inside and outside the screen."
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of admirers in the world, and in the hearts of each of us, that we were lucky enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were aired a few months ago with great success for the TNT channel.
It had already finished recording five of the chapters for the second season and a sixth was in the process, the chain reported.
There was no immediate statement from Warner or TNT on how the series would handle Hagman’s loss.
