Start a course that explores the "End of the World"
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible sting: The end of the “long countdown” of the Mayan Calendar, December 21, to which many people have clung as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what awaited him in the next couple of months: The cataclysmic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal precipice that some have called “deudarmagedon” and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where late-time Christian theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
“I didn’t realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester there has ever been,” Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If one analyzes what has been happening in the world today as if we were at 30 days and counting, this has been a really good period.
And remember that bad is good for those with an apocalyptic mindset.
And he’s not the only teacher who offers courses on the “end of the world” this semester, in theory the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Beautifulr is teaching the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World."
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We analyze why these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month the students analyzed films with apocalyptic themes and explored how they compare to real-life examples.
“I’ve tried to inform students about what’s possible, probable, credible and impossible,” said Beautifulr.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, Professor of Latin American History Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course, titled only “The End of the World.”
“We don’t add ‘2012’ to always have the option to re-learn the course, in case the world doesn’t end,” Restall said.
Despite the “imminent ruin,” students must study, generate projects and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work "until the same night the world is supposed to end," Restall said.
The courses were quite popular.
“It was saturated in two hours,” Restall said of his high-average student course, which was filled with 35 students.
We received emails for weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, from people asking if there was still a place.
Students, on the other hand, say that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It’s fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves,” said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old career student in Religion and Sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, in Rutgers-Camden.
And it is that the apocalyptic mentality, secular or religious, is only a matter of consolation or the absence of it.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing career student, said he had seen all the apocalyptic films.
“I had never heard of a class that could teach that,” he said.
I'm enjoying it.
But no student interviewed — let alone a professor — said to believe in the December 21 expiration date.
“Our first project dealt with Mayan prophecy and in a way we discredit it,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old West Chester senior at Temple.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it’s just a key point in the calendar, Restall said.
But he stressed that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, dating back several centuries, in which people react to the changes around them by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a surge in these speculations.
“In other places people don’t think about this,” he said.
Mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who teaches courses in the Philippines this year, quickly answered the question of whether he knew about any courses on the “end of the world” there.
“The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world,” he wrote, insinuating an exception from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years many days of the final trial have been talked about, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will start thinking immediately on the next date" or to philosophize that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the world will end.
Students and teachers are taking the date lightly.
Several said they plan to go to "end of the world" parties.
“Maybe call some friends so we can laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
